WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.257 --> 00:00:02.840
(bright music)

2
00:00:08.220 --> 00:00:09.510
<v Instructor>Okay, we're gonna go ahead</v>

3
00:00:09.510 --> 00:00:11.460
and get started then.

4
00:00:11.460 --> 00:00:13.590
So I have nothing to disclose still.

5
00:00:13.590 --> 00:00:15.120
You learned everything about me,

6
00:00:15.120 --> 00:00:16.320
even the stuff you don't want to know.

7
00:00:16.320 --> 00:00:17.460
Here are our learning objectives.

8
00:00:17.460 --> 00:00:20.220
Of course, the big one is dyspepsia,

9
00:00:20.220 --> 00:00:24.210
motility disorders, GERD and helicobacter,

10
00:00:24.210 --> 00:00:26.010
and peptic ulcer disease.

11
00:00:26.010 --> 00:00:30.420
So let's start with the top, which is esophageal disorders.

12
00:00:30.420 --> 00:00:32.070
You can have disorders of motility,

13
00:00:32.070 --> 00:00:33.960
you can have gastro-esophageal reflux,

14
00:00:33.960 --> 00:00:37.320
you can have inflammation, and you can have tumors.

15
00:00:37.320 --> 00:00:40.200
Now if we look at the symptoms from the esophagus,

16
00:00:40.200 --> 00:00:41.310
these are typically going to be

17
00:00:41.310 --> 00:00:44.760
some type of swallowing difficulty, like dysphasia.

18
00:00:44.760 --> 00:00:48.030
You can have pain, you can have heartburn,

19
00:00:48.030 --> 00:00:49.920
you can have chest pain,

20
00:00:49.920 --> 00:00:51.840
particularly if you have esophageal spasm.

21
00:00:51.840 --> 00:00:54.120
And then you have this issue of regurgitation,

22
00:00:54.120 --> 00:00:56.340
which is this effortless appearance

23
00:00:56.340 --> 00:01:00.930
of gastric contents up into the esophageal tract.

24
00:01:00.930 --> 00:01:02.820
Now, there are three basic disorders

25
00:01:02.820 --> 00:01:04.200
you have to worry about.

26
00:01:04.200 --> 00:01:06.420
Achalasia, spasm,

27
00:01:06.420 --> 00:01:09.780
which can be diffused or localized, and scleroderma.

28
00:01:09.780 --> 00:01:13.230
Now if we think about these particular disorders,

29
00:01:13.230 --> 00:01:16.860
they're all treated essentially the same exact way.

30
00:01:16.860 --> 00:01:20.640
Achalasia, which is the absence of peristaltic progression.

31
00:01:20.640 --> 00:01:22.530
You will see that these patients will present

32
00:01:22.530 --> 00:01:25.260
with dysphagia, both solids and liquids.

33
00:01:25.260 --> 00:01:26.850
They have a slightly increased risk

34
00:01:26.850 --> 00:01:28.680
of squamous cell carcinoma.

35
00:01:28.680 --> 00:01:31.050
We diagnose this by a barium swallow

36
00:01:31.050 --> 00:01:33.150
or some form of manometry.

37
00:01:33.150 --> 00:01:36.480
The treatment, like with diffuse esophageal spasm,

38
00:01:36.480 --> 00:01:38.880
is going to be a long-acting nitrate

39
00:01:38.880 --> 00:01:40.710
or a calcium channel blocker.

40
00:01:40.710 --> 00:01:42.210
Some of these patients will need to go on

41
00:01:42.210 --> 00:01:44.400
for a pneumatic dilatation.

42
00:01:44.400 --> 00:01:48.720
Now the spastic disorder is the diffuse esophageal spasm.

43
00:01:48.720 --> 00:01:50.610
This is the one you've always gotta think about.

44
00:01:50.610 --> 00:01:51.563
Could this be CAD?

45
00:01:51.563 --> 00:01:54.120
Because they will have what is appears to be

46
00:01:54.120 --> 00:01:56.670
the equivalent of chest pain.

47
00:01:56.670 --> 00:01:59.670
Barium swallow is the best way to diagnose it.

48
00:01:59.670 --> 00:02:02.400
We treat it the same way as achalasia.

49
00:02:02.400 --> 00:02:05.520
Now, scleroderma, thank goodness, is not common.

50
00:02:05.520 --> 00:02:08.460
But 90% of people who have scleroderma

51
00:02:08.460 --> 00:02:10.290
will eventually have involvement

52
00:02:10.290 --> 00:02:11.820
of the esophagus.

53
00:02:11.820 --> 00:02:13.620
They may present with no symptoms.

54
00:02:13.620 --> 00:02:15.600
They can have severe symptoms,

55
00:02:15.600 --> 00:02:17.940
not uncommon to find a stricture,

56
00:02:17.940 --> 00:02:20.730
and they will have motility abnormalities.

57
00:02:20.730 --> 00:02:22.260
We manage their reflux.

58
00:02:22.260 --> 00:02:24.060
We treat the esophagitis typically

59
00:02:24.060 --> 00:02:26.730
with an H2 blocker or a PPI.

60
00:02:26.730 --> 00:02:28.290
Some of these individuals though,

61
00:02:28.290 --> 00:02:32.370
will need a prokinetic drug, like metoclopramide

62
00:02:32.370 --> 00:02:34.740
or erythromycin.

63
00:02:34.740 --> 00:02:36.780
Now let's do an AES question here.

64
00:02:36.780 --> 00:02:41.550
We've got a 54-year-old woman who comes to the GI clinic

65
00:02:41.550 --> 00:02:44.520
with a history of GERD that has been unresponsive

66
00:02:44.520 --> 00:02:47.460
to maximum PPI therapy.

67
00:02:47.460 --> 00:02:50.550
She reports persistent heartburn, regurgitation,

68
00:02:50.550 --> 00:02:53.280
and nocturnal symptoms despite adhering

69
00:02:53.280 --> 00:02:56.580
to the optimized regimen for the past six months.

70
00:02:56.580 --> 00:02:59.760
She's otherwise healthy with no significant comorbidities.

71
00:02:59.760 --> 00:03:02.520
So what's the next step in her evaluation?

72
00:03:02.520 --> 00:03:07.470
Will we do esophageal manometry, 24 hour pH monitoring,

73
00:03:07.470 --> 00:03:11.163
barium radiology, or urea breath test?

74
00:03:16.230 --> 00:03:18.810
Okay, you know what this is?

75
00:03:18.810 --> 00:03:20.280
It's a learning opportunity.

76
00:03:20.280 --> 00:03:25.280
The correct answer here is a 24 hour pH monitoring,

77
00:03:25.350 --> 00:03:27.480
24 hour pH monitoring.

78
00:03:27.480 --> 00:03:30.870
The recommendation in the US is if you have GERD,

79
00:03:30.870 --> 00:03:34.830
we don't go routinely looking for helicobacter.

80
00:03:34.830 --> 00:03:36.870
If you practice in Europe, they do,

81
00:03:36.870 --> 00:03:39.540
but we don't do that in the US.

82
00:03:39.540 --> 00:03:42.990
Now in terms of diagnosing GERD, there's no gold standard.

83
00:03:42.990 --> 00:03:46.470
The EGD is used to assess complications.

84
00:03:46.470 --> 00:03:48.030
Now what would be those complications?

85
00:03:48.030 --> 00:03:49.770
We could see erosive esophagitis,

86
00:03:49.770 --> 00:03:53.160
a stricture, the ever popular Barrett's esophagus.

87
00:03:53.160 --> 00:03:56.643
We think about it, very uncommon, and then onto malignancy.

88
00:03:57.570 --> 00:04:00.150
But when we look at sensitivity and specificity,

89
00:04:00.150 --> 00:04:03.600
the EGD does not have adequate of either of those

90
00:04:03.600 --> 00:04:06.720
to determine pathologic reflux.

91
00:04:06.720 --> 00:04:08.310
So the diagnostic testing,

92
00:04:08.310 --> 00:04:10.860
esophageal manometry not recommended.

93
00:04:10.860 --> 00:04:12.690
The 24 hour pH monitoring,

94
00:04:12.690 --> 00:04:15.330
it's not recommended in the routine diagnosis of GERD

95
00:04:15.330 --> 00:04:18.390
and is not required in the presence of Barrett's.

96
00:04:18.390 --> 00:04:22.470
However, if you have refractory PPI therapy,

97
00:04:22.470 --> 00:04:25.770
then your gastroenterologist will put or can put

98
00:04:25.770 --> 00:04:29.850
a pH probe down into the lower esophagus

99
00:04:29.850 --> 00:04:34.560
to detect what the ongoing issue is there in terms of pH.

100
00:04:34.560 --> 00:04:38.070
Now, some would argue, how is this going to change anything?

101
00:04:38.070 --> 00:04:40.590
I'm still gonna have to maximize their PPI therapy.

102
00:04:40.590 --> 00:04:44.010
And would this be, though, a candidate for a fundoplication?

103
00:04:44.010 --> 00:04:45.180
That's the issue here.

104
00:04:45.180 --> 00:04:46.380
Would they be a surgical candidate?

105
00:04:46.380 --> 00:04:48.180
But remember, even with surgery,

106
00:04:48.180 --> 00:04:50.940
you're still going to need a PPI therapy, typically.

107
00:04:50.940 --> 00:04:53.160
Barium radiology: limited usefulness,

108
00:04:53.160 --> 00:04:54.240
it is not recommended.

109
00:04:54.240 --> 00:04:56.730
Now, in terms of screening for helicobacter,

110
00:04:56.730 --> 00:04:59.160
it is not recommended here.

111
00:04:59.160 --> 00:05:03.510
Eradication is not part of routine anti-reflux therapy.

112
00:05:03.510 --> 00:05:06.420
There's really insufficient evidence to recommend it

113
00:05:06.420 --> 00:05:10.140
in terms of all patients who need to be on a PPI.

114
00:05:10.140 --> 00:05:12.820
Now, if you do test them

115
00:05:13.980 --> 00:05:17.130
and they're found to be H. pylori positive,

116
00:05:17.130 --> 00:05:19.050
the recommendation is to treat them,

117
00:05:19.050 --> 00:05:22.920
but to let them know their GERD may not get any better,

118
00:05:22.920 --> 00:05:27.090
probably will not, and may actually get worse,

119
00:05:27.090 --> 00:05:31.470
because helicobacter has a net suppressive effect

120
00:05:31.470 --> 00:05:33.690
on acid production.

121
00:05:33.690 --> 00:05:36.420
So you can actually increase your acid production

122
00:05:36.420 --> 00:05:37.830
by eradicating it.

123
00:05:37.830 --> 00:05:39.000
So how do we diagnose it?

124
00:05:39.000 --> 00:05:41.280
An empiric trial of acid suppression therapy

125
00:05:41.280 --> 00:05:43.683
unless they have alarm symptoms.

126
00:05:45.000 --> 00:05:46.950
So when residents come into precept,

127
00:05:46.950 --> 00:05:48.540
they say, I'm gonna get a helicobacter,

128
00:05:48.540 --> 00:05:49.710
and I'm gonna start them on a PPI,

129
00:05:49.710 --> 00:05:50.913
I think this is GERD.

130
00:05:51.780 --> 00:05:54.240
Okay, you gotta make a decision here.

131
00:05:54.240 --> 00:05:57.180
You know, if they don't have any epigastric tenderness,

132
00:05:57.180 --> 00:06:00.660
likelihood is they do not have peptic ulcer disease

133
00:06:00.660 --> 00:06:04.143
or erosive gastritis.

134
00:06:05.010 --> 00:06:06.690
If they have alarm symptoms, of course,

135
00:06:06.690 --> 00:06:08.460
those patients are going to immediately go

136
00:06:08.460 --> 00:06:12.420
to assess complications potentially for GERD

137
00:06:12.420 --> 00:06:16.590
and an upper endoscopy would be needed.

138
00:06:16.590 --> 00:06:18.780
So here's the summary of the diagnostic testing.

139
00:06:18.780 --> 00:06:20.490
You can put that with your study materials

140
00:06:20.490 --> 00:06:22.230
as a summary slide.

141
00:06:22.230 --> 00:06:23.580
Now, the treatment.

142
00:06:23.580 --> 00:06:25.950
PPIs are more effective in relieving heartburn

143
00:06:25.950 --> 00:06:29.040
than our H2 or prokinetic agents.

144
00:06:29.040 --> 00:06:32.370
Different PPIs at the same or similar efficacy

145
00:06:32.370 --> 00:06:34.440
at standard doses.

146
00:06:34.440 --> 00:06:37.950
Long-term PPI use may increase fracture risk.

147
00:06:37.950 --> 00:06:39.840
But there's inconsistent evidence,

148
00:06:39.840 --> 00:06:42.990
when we look at hip fracture in particular.

149
00:06:42.990 --> 00:06:45.960
And then anti-secretory therapy has not been shown

150
00:06:45.960 --> 00:06:48.960
to reduce the need for recurrent dilatation

151
00:06:48.960 --> 00:06:51.363
secondary to stricture formation.

152
00:06:52.710 --> 00:06:55.263
Okay, here's our next AES question.

153
00:06:56.850 --> 00:06:59.220
Mr. Anderson is a 68-year-old male is scheduled

154
00:06:59.220 --> 00:07:03.000
for initiation on proton pump inhibitor therapy

155
00:07:03.000 --> 00:07:05.430
due to persistent symptoms of GERD.

156
00:07:05.430 --> 00:07:07.950
He has not received PPI treatment previously.

157
00:07:07.950 --> 00:07:10.080
You decide to discuss potential risks

158
00:07:10.080 --> 00:07:12.750
associated with therapy during the consult.

159
00:07:12.750 --> 00:07:14.040
In discussing initiation,

160
00:07:14.040 --> 00:07:16.410
which of the following is a potential risk of therapy

161
00:07:16.410 --> 00:07:18.060
that should be reviewed?

162
00:07:18.060 --> 00:07:19.950
Increased risk of B12 deficiency,

163
00:07:19.950 --> 00:07:22.020
enhanced likelihood of bacterial overgrowth,

164
00:07:22.020 --> 00:07:24.660
and an heightened susceptibility to allergic reactions,

165
00:07:24.660 --> 00:07:28.233
or an increased risk of iron deficiency anemia.

166
00:07:33.360 --> 00:07:34.710
Okay, the correct answer

167
00:07:34.710 --> 00:07:38.850
is an increased risk of vitamin B12 deficiency.

168
00:07:38.850 --> 00:07:41.793
So as we look at PPI therapy,

169
00:07:42.780 --> 00:07:45.330
here are the potential risks.

170
00:07:45.330 --> 00:07:47.010
Keeping in mind, because we don't know

171
00:07:47.010 --> 00:07:48.960
about the increased hip fracture risk,

172
00:07:48.960 --> 00:07:52.203
patients with known osteoporosis, you can still stay on it.

173
00:07:53.130 --> 00:07:56.130
There is an increased risk of hypomagnesemia,

174
00:07:56.130 --> 00:07:58.650
increased risk of B12 deficiency.

175
00:07:58.650 --> 00:08:00.810
Because spores now get through an environment

176
00:08:00.810 --> 00:08:04.080
in which there's a less acidic or higher pH,

177
00:08:04.080 --> 00:08:05.130
there's an increased risk

178
00:08:05.130 --> 00:08:07.440
of clostridium difficile infection.

179
00:08:07.440 --> 00:08:09.903
You may see an increase of CAP.

180
00:08:11.430 --> 00:08:13.140
So, community acquired pneumonia,

181
00:08:13.140 --> 00:08:16.260
there's a 27% increase in some series,

182
00:08:16.260 --> 00:08:19.020
and PPI therapy does not need to be altered

183
00:08:19.020 --> 00:08:21.090
if you're on concomitant clopidogrel.

184
00:08:21.090 --> 00:08:24.300
Now, if that's an issue in your local neck of the woods,

185
00:08:24.300 --> 00:08:25.410
worry about it there.

186
00:08:25.410 --> 00:08:28.800
But on the exam, you don't have to change anything.

187
00:08:28.800 --> 00:08:31.410
So here's a summary of our treatment, then.

188
00:08:31.410 --> 00:08:32.370
I wanna remind you,

189
00:08:32.370 --> 00:08:33.630
although you're gonna hear a lot

190
00:08:33.630 --> 00:08:35.850
about diet, lifestyle, and self-help measures,

191
00:08:35.850 --> 00:08:37.410
there's really limited evidence

192
00:08:37.410 --> 00:08:39.420
they make any difference.

193
00:08:39.420 --> 00:08:41.820
So as we think about GERD, one of the big things

194
00:08:41.820 --> 00:08:44.340
that makes a difference is weight loss.

195
00:08:44.340 --> 00:08:45.840
The second thing that makes a difference

196
00:08:45.840 --> 00:08:47.640
is avoiding peppermint.

197
00:08:47.640 --> 00:08:49.350
And the third thing that makes a difference

198
00:08:49.350 --> 00:08:51.720
is avoiding caffeine, like in coffee.

199
00:08:51.720 --> 00:08:53.850
'cause caffeine and peppermint

200
00:08:53.850 --> 00:08:56.613
actually relax the lower esophageal sphincter.

201
00:08:57.480 --> 00:09:01.260
If these other things contribute to your worsening GERD,

202
00:09:01.260 --> 00:09:04.020
then you're going to make modification as well.

203
00:09:04.020 --> 00:09:08.460
Now, if you have it when you lie down, then prop the bed up.

204
00:09:08.460 --> 00:09:11.820
You need to elevate it about eight to ten inches.

205
00:09:11.820 --> 00:09:14.700
You can use a wedge or a block.

206
00:09:14.700 --> 00:09:16.800
Pillows don't tend to help you very much,

207
00:09:16.800 --> 00:09:19.140
'cause they're just gonna bring your neck up a little bit.

208
00:09:19.140 --> 00:09:19.973
Okay?

209
00:09:21.000 --> 00:09:23.610
So here are the basic treatment guidelines.

210
00:09:23.610 --> 00:09:25.680
You don't see people with step one therapy.

211
00:09:25.680 --> 00:09:26.970
They have mild symptoms.

212
00:09:26.970 --> 00:09:29.100
They do a trial of patient directed therapy,

213
00:09:29.100 --> 00:09:32.160
and they adjusted their life as necessary.

214
00:09:32.160 --> 00:09:34.560
You start seeing them when they're no longer responding,

215
00:09:34.560 --> 00:09:37.200
but they typically have non erosive disease.

216
00:09:37.200 --> 00:09:39.870
You're gonna continue any lifestyle that makes a difference

217
00:09:39.870 --> 00:09:42.120
for them as an individual.

218
00:09:42.120 --> 00:09:44.610
PPI, maybe a pro motility agent,

219
00:09:44.610 --> 00:09:47.160
and they're gonna get eight to 12 weeks of therapy.

220
00:09:48.210 --> 00:09:49.140
Severe symptoms.

221
00:09:49.140 --> 00:09:50.250
These are the patients typically

222
00:09:50.250 --> 00:09:53.790
that need to go for an EGD to assess for complications.

223
00:09:53.790 --> 00:09:55.590
You're gonna continue the lifestyle measures.

224
00:09:55.590 --> 00:09:59.970
They go on a high dose H2 antagonist or a high dose PPI.

225
00:09:59.970 --> 00:10:03.390
Now, optimally, if they're on a scheduled PPI,

226
00:10:03.390 --> 00:10:05.190
you wanna do a 30 to 60 minutes

227
00:10:05.190 --> 00:10:06.840
before the first meal of the day.

228
00:10:06.840 --> 00:10:09.843
This has been shown to optimize effectiveness.

229
00:10:10.710 --> 00:10:12.090
Now what's the AGA say?

230
00:10:12.090 --> 00:10:15.120
If you've got a erosive esophagitis, you should be biopsied

231
00:10:15.120 --> 00:10:18.780
when there's concern of dysplasia or malignancy.

232
00:10:18.780 --> 00:10:20.940
They go on a daily proton pump inhibitor

233
00:10:20.940 --> 00:10:24.153
and they get a reevaluation in about eight weeks.

234
00:10:25.200 --> 00:10:28.680
If you're on pharmacologic treatment for GERD,

235
00:10:28.680 --> 00:10:30.780
long-term acid suppression therapy,

236
00:10:30.780 --> 00:10:34.440
you wanna titrate it to the lowest possible dose,

237
00:10:34.440 --> 00:10:37.050
and if possible, titrate them off

238
00:10:37.050 --> 00:10:39.843
of the PPI onto an H2 blocker.

239
00:10:40.980 --> 00:10:43.530
Now, how do we de-prescribe that medication?

240
00:10:43.530 --> 00:10:48.270
If I've got chronic GERD, it's recommended,

241
00:10:48.270 --> 00:10:51.210
particularly at those who are at low risk

242
00:10:51.210 --> 00:10:54.900
and are symptom free after four weeks of therapy.

243
00:10:54.900 --> 00:10:58.110
There are several methods that have been used.

244
00:10:58.110 --> 00:10:59.970
Some, though, if you abruptly stop,

245
00:10:59.970 --> 00:11:02.280
it will have a rebound acid production

246
00:11:02.280 --> 00:11:05.010
and have worsening of the symptoms.

247
00:11:05.010 --> 00:11:07.530
Now, we know that changing the PPI prescription

248
00:11:07.530 --> 00:11:12.000
to as needed results in about four pills per week

249
00:11:12.000 --> 00:11:13.440
being taken.

250
00:11:13.440 --> 00:11:15.120
So I get less pills.

251
00:11:15.120 --> 00:11:17.913
However, patients are not nearly as satisfied.

252
00:11:18.810 --> 00:11:21.240
Taking a PPI, though, as needed

253
00:11:21.240 --> 00:11:25.590
will decrease the need in about two thirds of patients.

254
00:11:25.590 --> 00:11:27.540
Okay, so that's dramatic.

255
00:11:27.540 --> 00:11:30.060
You can add a rescue histamine blocker

256
00:11:30.060 --> 00:11:32.940
that can maybe potentially reduce the risk

257
00:11:32.940 --> 00:11:37.500
of needing to restart the PPI upwards to about 80%.

258
00:11:37.500 --> 00:11:39.930
Now, if they need to be on long-term therapy,

259
00:11:39.930 --> 00:11:42.540
and I want to try to titrate it down,

260
00:11:42.540 --> 00:11:45.330
am I better to just discontinue it abruptly

261
00:11:45.330 --> 00:11:47.700
or titrate them off?

262
00:11:47.700 --> 00:11:50.520
It's a tossup.

263
00:11:50.520 --> 00:11:53.010
Whatever works for you and your patient practice.

264
00:11:53.010 --> 00:11:54.360
If I'm gonna titrate them off,

265
00:11:54.360 --> 00:11:56.370
I initially titrate them off over two weeks,

266
00:11:56.370 --> 00:11:57.840
and at the beginning of the second week,

267
00:11:57.840 --> 00:11:59.790
I will start the H2 blocker.

268
00:11:59.790 --> 00:12:02.043
But either can be used.

269
00:12:03.600 --> 00:12:05.970
Now, Barrett's, we think about this a lot.

270
00:12:05.970 --> 00:12:08.610
It is very uncommon.

271
00:12:08.610 --> 00:12:12.510
And if you have Barrett's, only about 1% will go on

272
00:12:12.510 --> 00:12:15.270
to develop adenocarcinoma.

273
00:12:15.270 --> 00:12:19.170
Now, who do we think about in terms of screening?

274
00:12:19.170 --> 00:12:22.620
Well, we need to screen those using an upper endoscopy,

275
00:12:22.620 --> 00:12:26.280
if they have at least three of the risk factors.

276
00:12:26.280 --> 00:12:28.800
And what are those risk factors?

277
00:12:28.800 --> 00:12:33.240
I am male, particularly, non-Hispanic white.

278
00:12:33.240 --> 00:12:34.650
I am maturing.

279
00:12:34.650 --> 00:12:36.630
I have chronic GERD, obesity,

280
00:12:36.630 --> 00:12:38.700
current or past history of smoking,

281
00:12:38.700 --> 00:12:41.280
and a confirmed family history of either Barrett's

282
00:12:41.280 --> 00:12:43.350
or esophageal adenocarcinoma.

283
00:12:43.350 --> 00:12:47.160
And that needs to be in a first degree relative. Okay?

284
00:12:47.160 --> 00:12:49.140
Screening women for Barrett's

285
00:12:49.140 --> 00:12:51.453
is like screening men for breast cancer.

286
00:12:52.380 --> 00:12:55.080
Very uncommon you're gonna find any issue.

287
00:12:55.080 --> 00:12:58.530
So you need three of those

288
00:12:58.530 --> 00:13:01.260
in order to potentially put forward

289
00:13:01.260 --> 00:13:04.800
that this patient should be screened for Barrett's.

290
00:13:04.800 --> 00:13:09.800
Now, if you have some type of related neoplasia,

291
00:13:10.800 --> 00:13:13.140
of course, those go on to an endoscopist

292
00:13:13.140 --> 00:13:16.593
for imaging, resection, and ablation.

293
00:13:17.550 --> 00:13:19.080
If you have Barrett's esophagus,

294
00:13:19.080 --> 00:13:19.913
you should be placed on

295
00:13:19.913 --> 00:13:22.050
at least a daily proton pump inhibitor.

296
00:13:22.050 --> 00:13:25.470
These are the individuals who do not have any neoplasia.

297
00:13:25.470 --> 00:13:28.920
If they have a nondysplastic Barrett's,

298
00:13:28.920 --> 00:13:33.920
they undergo surveillance at a minimum of three years, okay?

299
00:13:33.930 --> 00:13:36.480
A minimum of three years.

300
00:13:36.480 --> 00:13:40.680
Now, as we think about medical versus surgical treatment

301
00:13:40.680 --> 00:13:44.940
of GERD, you can do a laparoscopic fundoplication,

302
00:13:44.940 --> 00:13:47.220
but as we said, most of these patients are gonna continue

303
00:13:47.220 --> 00:13:49.410
to need medication.

304
00:13:49.410 --> 00:13:50.640
Endoscopic procedures.

305
00:13:50.640 --> 00:13:52.950
They may reduce some of the symptoms, though,

306
00:13:52.950 --> 00:13:56.790
and make the medication more effective.

307
00:13:56.790 --> 00:13:58.140
So here are a summary

308
00:13:58.140 --> 00:14:00.660
of our GERD treatment recommendations here,

309
00:14:00.660 --> 00:14:03.060
all the SOR criteria we've looked at.

310
00:14:03.060 --> 00:14:05.790
These two slides I would put with your study materials

311
00:14:05.790 --> 00:14:08.703
as a review of the topic we just discussed.

312
00:14:10.530 --> 00:14:13.953
Okay? Now, inflammatory disorders, esophagitis,

313
00:14:15.000 --> 00:14:16.140
what are we dealing with here?

314
00:14:16.140 --> 00:14:18.450
Well, it could be pill induced.

315
00:14:18.450 --> 00:14:21.660
You know, I'm taking ibuprofen.

316
00:14:21.660 --> 00:14:25.830
800 doesn't work for me, so I take 1200. Okay?

317
00:14:25.830 --> 00:14:29.430
Now keep in mind, just as an aside, ibuprofen is now known

318
00:14:29.430 --> 00:14:31.920
to have an analgesic ceiling effect.

319
00:14:31.920 --> 00:14:34.380
One of the largest studies to date now shows

320
00:14:34.380 --> 00:14:36.750
that in patients who come to an emergency department,

321
00:14:36.750 --> 00:14:37.740
this is where the study was done,

322
00:14:37.740 --> 00:14:40.080
70% of patients who have pain

323
00:14:40.080 --> 00:14:41.523
have musculoskeletal pain.

324
00:14:42.630 --> 00:14:45.030
And this particular study published about 18 months ago,

325
00:14:45.030 --> 00:14:48.300
looked at is 600 or 800 any better than 400?

326
00:14:48.300 --> 00:14:51.450
And what the randomized controlled trial showed was, no.

327
00:14:51.450 --> 00:14:53.280
So how's that changed practice for me?

328
00:14:53.280 --> 00:14:54.660
Well, if you come in and you say, listen,

329
00:14:54.660 --> 00:14:57.090
I'm taking 400 of ibuprofen for this shoulder pain

330
00:14:57.090 --> 00:14:58.980
four times a day, and it's no help,

331
00:14:58.980 --> 00:15:01.020
I don't increase it to 600 or 800.

332
00:15:01.020 --> 00:15:02.400
I actually change the class

333
00:15:02.400 --> 00:15:05.370
of the non-steroidal anti-inflammatory drug.

334
00:15:05.370 --> 00:15:09.510
If you're on 600 or 800 for analgesia, I tell you,

335
00:15:09.510 --> 00:15:11.730
give it a try at 400.

336
00:15:11.730 --> 00:15:14.670
Now, we know that acetaminophen potentiates the effects

337
00:15:14.670 --> 00:15:17.970
of non-steroidals like it does narcotics.

338
00:15:17.970 --> 00:15:19.950
So my regimen for patients is always,

339
00:15:19.950 --> 00:15:22.890
if they're gonna use ibuprofen or any NSAID,

340
00:15:22.890 --> 00:15:25.410
they take 325 to 500 of acetaminophen

341
00:15:25.410 --> 00:15:27.360
with that particular NSAID.

342
00:15:27.360 --> 00:15:31.410
So for example, ibuprofen, 400 milligrams four times a day.

343
00:15:31.410 --> 00:15:34.740
You would take that with 325 to 500 of acetaminophen

344
00:15:34.740 --> 00:15:36.630
simultaneously.

345
00:15:36.630 --> 00:15:37.830
Now, infective,

346
00:15:37.830 --> 00:15:40.710
these are mostly in immunocompromised patients,

347
00:15:40.710 --> 00:15:42.240
could be viral, it could be fungal,

348
00:15:42.240 --> 00:15:44.310
corrosive, of course, if you consume something,

349
00:15:44.310 --> 00:15:45.480
you're gonna have a problem.

350
00:15:45.480 --> 00:15:47.280
And then eosinophilic.

351
00:15:47.280 --> 00:15:48.540
Now this is not common,

352
00:15:48.540 --> 00:15:51.300
but it's an allergic reaction appears in most people.

353
00:15:51.300 --> 00:15:52.770
But for some it's idiopathic.

354
00:15:52.770 --> 00:15:55.290
We treat this, though, like an allergic reaction

355
00:15:55.290 --> 00:15:59.130
with steroids and anti-allergy medications, okay?

356
00:15:59.130 --> 00:16:00.060
They will typically have

357
00:16:00.060 --> 00:16:04.230
a pronounced eosinophil infiltration on biopsy.

358
00:16:04.230 --> 00:16:06.330
And you will see a peripheral eosinophilia,

359
00:16:06.330 --> 00:16:07.803
not uncommonly as well.

360
00:16:08.730 --> 00:16:12.843
Now, esophageal tumors, 90% of these are gonna be cancer.

361
00:16:13.800 --> 00:16:14.670
There are two forms.

362
00:16:14.670 --> 00:16:16.290
There's squamous cell carcinoma.

363
00:16:16.290 --> 00:16:17.820
This is the one that's associated

364
00:16:17.820 --> 00:16:20.730
with heavy alcohol and smoking.

365
00:16:20.730 --> 00:16:24.240
The adenocarcinoma, as we said, GERD is the risk factor.

366
00:16:24.240 --> 00:16:27.630
And the risk there is what makes my GERD worse?

367
00:16:27.630 --> 00:16:29.460
Well, obesity and tobacco use.

368
00:16:29.460 --> 00:16:32.970
So it's an indirect cause, not a direct cause

369
00:16:32.970 --> 00:16:34.713
of increasing the risk.

370
00:16:36.330 --> 00:16:38.820
Now, diseases of the stomach.

371
00:16:38.820 --> 00:16:40.200
Acid peptic disorders,

372
00:16:40.200 --> 00:16:42.810
infections, motor disorders, and cancer.

373
00:16:42.810 --> 00:16:46.110
Let's go for this as we look at this question.

374
00:16:46.110 --> 00:16:47.640
49-year-old female comes in

375
00:16:47.640 --> 00:16:50.280
with a four week history of epigastric pain.

376
00:16:50.280 --> 00:16:52.200
She reports the pain gets better when she eats,

377
00:16:52.200 --> 00:16:55.350
but gets worse about an hour after eating.

378
00:16:55.350 --> 00:16:57.540
She's been using an over-the-counter liquid antacid,

379
00:16:57.540 --> 00:17:00.180
which she reports decreases her symptoms.

380
00:17:00.180 --> 00:17:02.707
She denies weight loss, hematemesis, melena,

381
00:17:02.707 --> 00:17:04.230
or hematochezia.

382
00:17:04.230 --> 00:17:07.590
Except for the mid epigastric tenderness,

383
00:17:07.590 --> 00:17:08.970
her exam is unremarkable.

384
00:17:08.970 --> 00:17:11.820
Her only medication is periodic acetaminophen.

385
00:17:11.820 --> 00:17:14.160
She uses that for her headaches.

386
00:17:14.160 --> 00:17:15.960
So which of the following diagnostic tests

387
00:17:15.960 --> 00:17:18.420
would you recommend in her evaluation?

388
00:17:18.420 --> 00:17:23.190
A serum gastrin, helicobacter pylori serology,

389
00:17:23.190 --> 00:17:27.633
an EGD, or get a urea breath test on her?

390
00:17:33.750 --> 00:17:35.400
Close to a learning opportunity,

391
00:17:35.400 --> 00:17:39.720
but the correct answer is a urea breath test.

392
00:17:39.720 --> 00:17:43.710
You want a test for active infection.

393
00:17:43.710 --> 00:17:47.220
Now, when we're thinking about dyspepsia,

394
00:17:47.220 --> 00:17:50.583
this is epigastric pain, discomfort, or burning sensation.

395
00:17:51.540 --> 00:17:53.700
Peptic ulcer disease can include

396
00:17:53.700 --> 00:17:55.563
gastric and duodenal ulcers.

397
00:17:56.670 --> 00:17:59.490
Peptic ulcer disease is most commonly caused

398
00:17:59.490 --> 00:18:04.350
by helicobacter pylori and the use of NSAIDs.

399
00:18:04.350 --> 00:18:06.390
Now, why do we develop these?

400
00:18:06.390 --> 00:18:08.910
Well, there's this imbalance between what protects

401
00:18:08.910 --> 00:18:10.920
and the aggressive factors.

402
00:18:10.920 --> 00:18:12.330
So the protective factors, you know,

403
00:18:12.330 --> 00:18:14.790
we have these surface epithelial cells.

404
00:18:14.790 --> 00:18:17.730
Oh, it's like snuggling into mashed potatoes.

405
00:18:17.730 --> 00:18:21.150
It's just all of this mucus and bicarbonate,

406
00:18:21.150 --> 00:18:23.040
that's so lovely.

407
00:18:23.040 --> 00:18:26.250
And we've got these specialized apical surface membranes,

408
00:18:26.250 --> 00:18:27.870
all this prostaglandin.

409
00:18:27.870 --> 00:18:30.330
And then we come along, and, you know,

410
00:18:30.330 --> 00:18:33.780
we're taking 1200 of ibuprofen four times a day.

411
00:18:33.780 --> 00:18:35.490
We wanna be on high dose steroids,

412
00:18:35.490 --> 00:18:37.290
'cause we went to urgent care.

413
00:18:37.290 --> 00:18:39.480
We smoke three packs a day,

414
00:18:39.480 --> 00:18:43.650
we're drinking a 40 ounce or two a beer a day,

415
00:18:43.650 --> 00:18:45.873
probably not diet.

416
00:18:46.800 --> 00:18:48.210
And it's ongoing,

417
00:18:48.210 --> 00:18:50.730
as to whether stress is going to cause this.

418
00:18:50.730 --> 00:18:53.280
Because, I will tell you, I have yet to meet a patient

419
00:18:53.280 --> 00:18:54.603
who is not stressed.

420
00:18:55.560 --> 00:18:58.470
Like you guys are all in here stressed.

421
00:18:58.470 --> 00:19:03.000
Most dyspepsia is not peptic ulcer disease.

422
00:19:03.000 --> 00:19:04.413
It's functional.

423
00:19:06.330 --> 00:19:07.560
It's functional.

424
00:19:07.560 --> 00:19:08.970
Now, how do we diagnose this

425
00:19:08.970 --> 00:19:11.520
with the Rome IV diagnostic criteria?

426
00:19:11.520 --> 00:19:13.650
You need the presence of at least one of the following:

427
00:19:13.650 --> 00:19:15.540
postprandial fullness, three days per week,

428
00:19:15.540 --> 00:19:18.360
early satiety, epigastric pain, epigastric burning,

429
00:19:18.360 --> 00:19:20.733
and no evidence of structural disease.

430
00:19:21.780 --> 00:19:23.520
We all have these patients,

431
00:19:23.520 --> 00:19:27.000
they take a look down there, they don't find anything. Okay?

432
00:19:27.000 --> 00:19:31.710
Now, 25% of people who come in with dyspepsia

433
00:19:31.710 --> 00:19:35.400
will have some type of organic issue,

434
00:19:35.400 --> 00:19:39.450
but 75% are gonna have functional dyspepsia.

435
00:19:39.450 --> 00:19:41.280
Functional dyspepsia, okay?

436
00:19:41.280 --> 00:19:44.550
Now, what about the medications?

437
00:19:44.550 --> 00:19:46.080
These are the ones you have to worry about.

438
00:19:46.080 --> 00:19:50.013
Any antibiotic, steroids, herbs,

439
00:19:50.880 --> 00:19:54.510
especially if they're taking the white willow bark. Okay?

440
00:19:54.510 --> 00:19:57.423
Iron, Metformin,

441
00:19:58.260 --> 00:20:00.750
NSAIDs, Orlistat,

442
00:20:00.750 --> 00:20:02.010
or as my patients say,

443
00:20:02.010 --> 00:20:04.923
the most expensive laxative you'll ever take.

444
00:20:06.191 --> 00:20:09.240
Dr. Veil didn't point out on the package insert, it says,

445
00:20:09.240 --> 00:20:10.986
don't wear white pants.

446
00:20:10.986 --> 00:20:14.190
(audience laughing)

447
00:20:14.190 --> 00:20:15.390
Potassium chloride, theo.

448
00:20:15.390 --> 00:20:17.190
I mean, theophylline,

449
00:20:17.190 --> 00:20:19.380
when was the last time you saw somebody on theophylline?

450
00:20:19.380 --> 00:20:21.750
You know, that's like dig.

451
00:20:21.750 --> 00:20:23.190
Although some of you, when you were in training,

452
00:20:23.190 --> 00:20:24.570
everybody was on theophylline,

453
00:20:24.570 --> 00:20:25.920
and you remember being in the NICU,

454
00:20:25.920 --> 00:20:27.930
they were all on aminophylline.

455
00:20:27.930 --> 00:20:29.133
You remember that?

456
00:20:30.390 --> 00:20:31.223
People here talking,

457
00:20:31.223 --> 00:20:32.790
what in the world are they talking about?

458
00:20:32.790 --> 00:20:33.873
Aminophylline.

459
00:20:35.100 --> 00:20:36.600
Now, here are the clinical indications

460
00:20:36.600 --> 00:20:39.540
associated with possible etiologies, though.

461
00:20:39.540 --> 00:20:40.740
I'm growing more mature,

462
00:20:40.740 --> 00:20:43.170
and I gotta think now about malignancy.

463
00:20:43.170 --> 00:20:45.810
I got pain, particularly it's radiating to the back,

464
00:20:45.810 --> 00:20:47.100
the right upper quadrant,

465
00:20:47.100 --> 00:20:49.860
then I'm thinking of biliary or pancreatic process.

466
00:20:49.860 --> 00:20:51.480
Vomiting or severe nausea,

467
00:20:51.480 --> 00:20:54.423
I could have gastroparesis.

468
00:20:56.580 --> 00:20:58.110
Here's the diagnostic approach.

469
00:20:58.110 --> 00:21:00.180
Always, history and physical exam to start.

470
00:21:00.180 --> 00:21:03.300
The laboratory is going to affirm my diagnosis.

471
00:21:03.300 --> 00:21:05.010
How much NSAID are you taking?

472
00:21:05.010 --> 00:21:06.720
Are there any warning signs?

473
00:21:06.720 --> 00:21:08.730
Is there nausea and vomiting?

474
00:21:08.730 --> 00:21:11.640
The physical exam is typically going to be normal,

475
00:21:11.640 --> 00:21:14.730
except for the fact that you've got epigastric tenderness.

476
00:21:14.730 --> 00:21:17.400
And then the laboratory tests, really,

477
00:21:17.400 --> 00:21:20.970
they should only be used when you're identifying patients

478
00:21:20.970 --> 00:21:22.890
with alarm features.

479
00:21:22.890 --> 00:21:25.770
Otherwise, they're not really gonna tell you much.

480
00:21:25.770 --> 00:21:27.780
Now, here are the alarm features I'm worried about

481
00:21:27.780 --> 00:21:29.490
with dyspepsia.

482
00:21:29.490 --> 00:21:32.790
Of course, anytime unintentional weight loss,

483
00:21:32.790 --> 00:21:35.370
difficulty swallowing, pain on swallowing.

484
00:21:35.370 --> 00:21:37.650
I can't explain why you have iron deficiency anemia.

485
00:21:37.650 --> 00:21:40.200
Why are you having this vomiting?

486
00:21:40.200 --> 00:21:42.000
Okay, I got a palpable mass.

487
00:21:42.000 --> 00:21:44.460
Or, you know, there's a supraclavicular node.

488
00:21:44.460 --> 00:21:46.560
I got a family history of upper GI cancer.

489
00:21:46.560 --> 00:21:48.870
Those are the ones I'm being concerned about

490
00:21:48.870 --> 00:21:50.250
when I'm thinking about dyspepsia

491
00:21:50.250 --> 00:21:51.870
and where I need to go looking.

492
00:21:51.870 --> 00:21:56.400
So the diagnostic approach here is if you're over 60,

493
00:21:56.400 --> 00:21:59.520
basically you need an EGD with biopsies,

494
00:21:59.520 --> 00:22:01.860
and at the same time you will get

495
00:22:01.860 --> 00:22:06.860
a urease activity examination during the time of the EGD

496
00:22:06.930 --> 00:22:08.763
to look for H. pylori.

497
00:22:09.720 --> 00:22:12.960
If you're younger than 60, of course you're gonna be tested

498
00:22:12.960 --> 00:22:15.000
and treated for H. pylori,

499
00:22:15.000 --> 00:22:20.000
and selectively you're going to do an upper endoscopy.

500
00:22:20.160 --> 00:22:23.280
Now, in terms of H. pylori, you wanna do a test

501
00:22:23.280 --> 00:22:25.263
for active infection.

502
00:22:26.580 --> 00:22:28.500
Active infection,

503
00:22:28.500 --> 00:22:31.020
and that would be either a stool antigen test,

504
00:22:31.020 --> 00:22:35.220
or we would be using a breath urea test

505
00:22:35.220 --> 00:22:38.040
or urea breath test. Okay?

506
00:22:38.040 --> 00:22:41.670
Most patients who have a normal upper endoscopy,

507
00:22:41.670 --> 00:22:44.160
and routine laboratory tests are normal,

508
00:22:44.160 --> 00:22:48.930
they're gonna have functional dyspepsia. Okay?

509
00:22:48.930 --> 00:22:51.930
Now, if we think about those who we test

510
00:22:51.930 --> 00:22:55.050
for helicobacter pylori, if they're negative,

511
00:22:55.050 --> 00:22:57.960
they get empiric proton pump inhibitor treatment.

512
00:22:57.960 --> 00:23:00.393
If they're positive, they get treated.

513
00:23:03.390 --> 00:23:08.163
Now, in terms of how we're going to move with eradication,

514
00:23:09.120 --> 00:23:12.870
if we look at functional dyspepsia and eradication,

515
00:23:12.870 --> 00:23:15.570
you can see there the number needed to treat is eight.

516
00:23:16.860 --> 00:23:18.120
If you are a patient, though,

517
00:23:18.120 --> 00:23:20.610
and your H. pylori is negative, it's functional,

518
00:23:20.610 --> 00:23:23.310
they should still be started on a PPI.

519
00:23:23.310 --> 00:23:24.960
Now, in terms of acid suppression

520
00:23:24.960 --> 00:23:26.733
and functional dyspepsia.

521
00:23:28.230 --> 00:23:31.410
Standard daily doses, and typically these are taken

522
00:23:31.410 --> 00:23:32.460
for about eight weeks,

523
00:23:32.460 --> 00:23:35.400
they're superior to placebo for reduction

524
00:23:35.400 --> 00:23:38.730
of their functional dyspepsia symptoms.

525
00:23:38.730 --> 00:23:41.070
Long-term PPIs, so you gotta be careful here.

526
00:23:41.070 --> 00:23:43.530
Chronic kidney disease, potential for bone fracture,

527
00:23:43.530 --> 00:23:47.250
as we said, C. diff infection, community acquired pneumonia,

